Ripple Labs Inc. is a company that raised money to build a global interbank=
 payments network by selling hundreds of millions of dollars of a crypto to=
ken, XRP, that would be valuable if it succeeded in building that network. =
In 2020, the US Securities and Exchange Commission sued Ripple, arguing tha=
t it was doing unregistered securities offerings when it sold this speculat=
ive investment to fund its business. On Thursday, the federal judge in the =
case, Analisa Torres,  handed down an opinion finding that Ripple=C2=A0was=
=C2=A0doing unregistered securities offerings when it sold XRP directly to =
institutional purchasers, but it was=C2=A0not=C2=A0doing unregistered secur=
ities offerings when it sold hundreds of millions of dollars of XRP to anon=
ymous purchasers on crypto exchanges.
I found this strange, and I   wrote about it on Friday. I guess my main poi=
nts were (1) it is strange for XRP to sometimes be a security and sometimes=
 not and (2) if it=C2=A0is=C2=A0going to be sometimes a security and someti=
mes not, it is strange to give the protections of the securities laws=C2=A0=
only=C2=A0to sophisticated institutional buyers who conduct due diligence a=
nd negotiate directly with the issuers, and not to public buyers on exchang=
es.
People got mad at me about this. The main objection goes something like thi=
s:
=09XRP is never itself a security. It is just some computer code, =E2=80=9C=
little more than [an] alphanumeric cryptographic sequence,=E2=80=9D as the =
court says, citing another crypto case.=C2=A0=09Sometimes, when Ripple sold=
 XRP, those sales were =E2=80=9Cinvestment contracts=E2=80=9D under the US =
Supreme Court=E2=80=99s Howey test: They were=C2=A0=E2=80=9Can investment o=
f money in a common enterprise with profits to come solely from the efforts=
 of others,=E2=80=9D because the whole transaction that Ripple did with its=
 investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0institutional investors who bought XRP in direct =
over-the-counter=C2=A0trades with Ripple =E2=80=94=C2=A0feels like an inves=
tment contract.=09Other times, when Ripple sold XRP, they were not, because=
 the whole transaction just occurred anonymously, on an exchange, so there =
were no direct arrangements with the buyers and no expectation by the buyer=
s that Ripple would make efforts to make XRP profitable.

The analogy=C2=A0that everyone in crypto likes to use is =E2=80=9Cthe orang=
es in Howey were not securities.=E2=80=9D (Howey, which we discussed on Fri=
day, is the  Supreme Court case that created the test for an =E2=80=9Cinves=
tment contract=E2=80=9D: W.J. Howey Co. sold people some orange groves alon=
g with management services, promising to split the orange profits with the =
buyers; the Supreme Court found this to be a security.)
I think that this is wrong. You can eat an orange. XRP is not an orange; it=
 is purely an abstract creation of Ripple, whose value comes entirely from =
the entrepreneurial efforts of Ripple.=C2=A0Nobody bought XRP to eat it. No=
r did anyone buy XRP just because they like owning =E2=80=9Calphanumeric cr=
yptographic sequences.=E2=80=9D There are two reasons you might buy XRP:
=09You want to=C2=A0use=C2=A0XRP. XRP is the currency of the XRP blockchain=
, developed by Ripple=E2=80=99s founders=C2=A0to facilitate cross-border pa=
yments and banking services. My understanding is that, in its decade of ope=
ration, Ripple has not gotten all that far in signing up banks for this pay=
ment network, but XRP=C2=A0is=C2=A0a functioning cryptocurrency with a bloc=
kchain that does transactions, and this is a possible reason for buying XRP=
. (It is=C2=A0certainly=C2=A0a possible=C2=A0reason for buying=C2=A0other c=
ryptocurrencies, like Ethereum, that are regularly used to pay for transact=
ions on widely used blockchains.)=C2=A0There is essentially no discussion o=
f this possibility in the opinion, though, and I do not think that anyone i=
s pounding the table for the view that a lot of the people buying XRP on ex=
changes were doing so in order to facilitate bank transfers. (If anything, =
the over-the-counter buyers would include banks who want to actually use XR=
P =E2=80=94=C2=A0but some OTC buyers explicitly disclaimed the possibility =
of using XRP.
  [1]
)=C2=A0=09You think that the price of XRP will go up. Why would it go up? W=
ell, the possibilities include (a) =E2=80=9Cgeneral cryptocurrency market t=
rends=E2=80=9D (in Judge Torres=E2=80=99 words) and (b) Ripple succeeds in =
building a widely used payments network, which makes XRP more valuable.

Judge Torres concludes that Ripple=E2=80=99s institutional buyers of XRP bo=
ught it for Reason 2(b): Ripple told them that it would make XRP more valua=
ble:
Based on the totality of circumstances, the Court finds that reasonable inv=
estors, situated in the position of the Institutional Buyers, would have pu=
rchased XRP with the expectation that they would derive profits from Ripple=
=E2=80=99s efforts. From Ripple=E2=80=99s communications, marketing campaig=
n, and the nature of the Institutional Sales, reasonable investors would un=
derstand that Ripple would use the capital received from its Institutional =
Sales to improve the market for XRP and develop uses for the XRP Ledger, th=
ereby increasing the value of XRP.
Fine. But my contention is that these sales did not consist of (1) XRP=C2=
=A0plus=C2=A0(2) some set of contracts promising that Ripple would use the =
money to increase the value of XRP. They consisted only of XRP.
  [2]
=C2=A0Institutions did not enter into a contract =E2=80=94=C2=A0like the co=
ntract in Howey =E2=80=94=C2=A0in which Ripple promised to manage a grove o=
f XRP for them and give them the proceeds of their success. They just bough=
t XRP. The XRP, and the way in which=C2=A0Ripple advertised it, was=C2=A0it=
self=C2=A0a bet on Ripple=E2=80=99s entrepreneurial efforts.
And my second contention is that this is exactly as true in all respects fo=
r the retail buyers who bought XRP from Ripple on crypto exchanges. Like th=
e institutional buyers, they were buying a speculative asset that would go =
up or down, in the long run,=C2=A0exclusively due to Ripple=E2=80=99s entre=
preneurial efforts. They might not have had as sophisticated understanding =
of these mechanisms as the institutional investors, but =E2=80=9Cretail inv=
estors are under-informed and confused=E2=80=9D has never in the past been =
a reason to=C2=A0deny=C2=A0them the protections of the securities laws.
Let=E2=80=99s say that Ripple succeeds wildly and XRP becomes the linchpin =
of a global payments network. Then the XRP that Ripple=E2=80=99s institutio=
nal investors bought would go up, and they would have a good return on thei=
r investment. The return on investment would come=C2=A0exclusively=C2=A0fro=
m the increasing value of their XRP: They had no=C2=A0other=C2=A0contracts =
with Ripple, nothing else that would entitle them to any return outside of =
their XRP. The XRP, for them,=C2=A0is=C2=A0the =E2=80=9Csecurity=E2=80=9D; =
it is the speculative instrument that they invested money in hoping to get =
a return from Ripple=E2=80=99s efforts.
But that is exactly as true, in exactly the same way, for the retail invest=
ors who bought XRP on the exchange. Those retail investors are in complete =
commonality with the institutional investors; they bought the same thing an=
d have exactly the same exposure to exactly the same risks. If Ripple succe=
eds wildly, a person who bought 100 XRP from Ripple on the exchange will ge=
t exactly the same benefit as the institution who bought 100 XRP from Rippl=
e directly. If XRP is a security in the hands of that institution, because =
it was =E2=80=9Can investment of money in a common enterprise with profits =
to come solely from the efforts of others,=E2=80=9D then I think it is a se=
curity in the hands of the exchange buyer: same money, same enterprise, sam=
e profits from same efforts of same others.
And my third contention is that they bought them for the same reasons. Sure=
 sure sure: Some retail investors who bought XRP on the exchange from Rippl=
e did not actually see Ripple=E2=80=99s advertisements, its website, its wh=
ite paper, its Reddit posts, its YouTube videos, or the other public statem=
ents in which Ripple said that it would work to=C2=A0increase the value of =
XRP, the public statements that Judge Torres thought made XRP a security wi=
th respect to the institutional investors. But it would be very strange ind=
eed if nobody did, if everybody bought XRP solely because they liked alphan=
umeric sequences. Surely Ripple=E2=80=99s widespread=C2=A0advertising of XR=
P as an investment in its business=C2=A0is what caused people generally to =
want to buy XRP; it=E2=80=99s what created the market for XRP.
And so if you bought XRP without ever seeing any of those advertisements, j=
ust because you logged onto a crypto exchange and saw the price of XRP goin=
g up and thought =E2=80=9Cokay I=E2=80=99ll buy that,=E2=80=9D I would argu=
e that you were buying a security just like those institutional investors. =
Meta Platforms Inc. stock does not become any less stock because you don=E2=
=80=99t buy it directly from Meta, or because you have not read Meta=E2=80=
=99s securities filings. The statements that a company makes to a buyer of =
its securities create the market for those securities, and if you are buyin=
g the securities in the aftermarket it is ultimately because of those state=
ments.
In Ripple,=C2=A0Judge Torres found that Ripple went around making public st=
atements promising to build a business to make XRP more valuable, and she f=
ound that those statements were enough to make Ripple=E2=80=99s XRP sales s=
ecurities offerings,=C2=A0if you could prove that the buyers read them, as =
the institutional buyers did.=C2=A0But since you can=E2=80=99t prove that a=
bout anonymous buyers on the exchange, on exchange-sales can never be secur=
ities offerings. Ripple could have put ads on the subway and on television =
and on Twitter saying =E2=80=9Cbuy XRP and we will use your money to build =
an ecosystem and make you rich,=E2=80=9D and then sold XRP on exchanges, an=
d it would not, in the logic of this opinion, be a securities offering, bec=
ause no buyer of XRP on the exchange could be=C2=A0sure=C2=A0they were buyi=
ng it from Ripple, and no court could be=C2=A0sure=C2=A0that the buyers had=
 seen the ads. I just don=E2=80=99t think that can be the way securities la=
w works?
The implications of this decision are very strange. Here is one:
=09A company can create a crypto token, declare that there are 100 billion =
tokens, and issue=C2=A0all=C2=A0of them to itself. No mining, no decentrali=
zation, just 100% owned by one company.=09The token can have=C2=A0no=C2=A0u=
se: It can=E2=80=99t be used to run smart contracts or pay for services on =
a network or even to make international payments; it can=C2=A0only=C2=A0be =
traded on exchanges for dollars.=09The company can go around advertising, p=
ublicly, in every venue, to every retail and institutional investor, that t=
he token will be incredibly valuable due to the company=E2=80=99s efforts t=
o create an ecosystem and build its network.=09The company can even=C2=A0ex=
plicitly say that it will share the profits of its business=C2=A0with token=
 holders, by using profits to do buybacks.=09Then it can sell the token to =
public investors on crypto exchanges to raise money to build the business.=
=09This is not a security, because no one can prove that the anonymous buye=
rs on the exchange saw the=C2=A0advertisements,=C2=A0and so not subject to =
securities laws.

I am not saying that this is actually what Ripple did, though it is close. =
(Ripple does not do No. 4, and arguably No. 2 isn=E2=80=99t quite true of X=
RP.) I am saying: Look at that list and tell me that the token is not a spe=
culative investment in a business, tell me that it is not, in the Supreme C=
ourt=E2=80=99s words in Howey, one of =E2=80=9Cthe countless and variable s=
chemes devised by those who seek the use of the money of others on the prom=
ise of profits.=E2=80=9D Tell me that this is not what the securities laws =
were meant to regulate.
Now, I should say, a reasonable answer to all of this might be =E2=80=9Csur=
e, there should be a disclosure and regulatory regime for crypto offerings =
that is roughly parallel to the one for securities, but that addresses the =
unique features of crypto.=E2=80=9D And I   agree with the crypto industry =
that the SEC=E2=80=99s approach to crypto is not so much about crafting app=
ropriate disclosure rules as it is about=C2=A0shutting down crypto.   I hav=
e suggested that, after last year=E2=80=99s crypto winter and the collapse =
of FTX Trading Ltd., the SEC=E2=80=99s crackdown is politically well-timed:=
