<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Ripple</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ripple Labs Inc. is a company that raised mone=
y to build a global interbank payments network by selling hundreds of milli=
ons of dollars of a crypto token, XRP, that would be valuable if it succeed=
ed in building that network. In 2020, the US Securities and Exchange Commis=
sion sued Ripple, arguing that it was doing unregistered securities offerin=
gs when it sold this speculative investment to fund its business. On Thursd=
ay, the federal judge in the case, Analisa Torres, <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32105300.262411/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC=
5pby9kb2N1bWVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JWcXlMRnlFWm56OC92MA/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB73a2d030" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> handed down an opinion</a> finding that R=
ipple=C2=A0<em>was=C2=A0</em>doing unregistered securities offerings when i=
t sold XRP directly to institutional purchasers, but it was=C2=A0<em>not=C2=
=A0</em>doing unregistered securities offerings when it sold hundreds of mi=
llions of dollars of XRP to anonymous purchasers on crypto exchanges.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I found this strange, and I <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32105300.262411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDctMTQvcmlwcGxlLWlzLWEtc2VjdXJ=
pdHktYW5kLWl0LWlzbi10P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA3MTcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW=
1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDcxNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249b=
W9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6a40cc6e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  wrote about it o=
n Friday</a>. I guess my main points were (1) it is strange for XRP to some=
times be a security and sometimes not and (2) if it=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>g=
oing to be sometimes a security and sometimes not, it is strange to give th=
e protections of the securities laws=C2=A0<em>only=C2=A0</em>to sophisticat=
ed institutional buyers who conduct due diligence and negotiate directly wi=
th the issuers, and <em>not</em> to public buyers on exchanges.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">People got mad at me about this. The main obje=
ction goes something like this:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">XRP is never <em>itself </em>a securi=
ty. It is just some computer code, =E2=80=9Clittle more than [an] alphanume=
ric cryptographic sequence,=E2=80=9D as <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/32105300.262411/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1b=
WVudHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JWcXlMRnlFWm56OC92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cC73a2d030" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">the court says</a>, citing another crypto case.=C2=A0=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Sometimes, when Ripple sold XRP, =
those sales were =E2=80=9Cinvestment contracts=E2=80=9D under the US Suprem=
e Court=E2=80=99s Howey test: They were=C2=A0=E2=80=9Can investment of mone=
y in a common enterprise with profits to come solely from the efforts of ot=
hers,=E2=80=9D because the whole transaction that Ripple did with its inves=
tors =E2=80=94=C2=A0institutional investors who bought XRP in direct over-t=
he-counter=C2=A0trades with Ripple =E2=80=94=C2=A0feels like an investment =
contract.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Other times, when Ripple=
 sold XRP, they were not, because the whole transaction just occurred anony=
mously, on an exchange, so there were no direct arrangements with the buyer=
s and no expectation by the buyers that Ripple would make efforts to make X=
RP profitable.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The analogy=C2=A0that everyone in crypto likes=
 to use is =E2=80=9Cthe oranges in Howey were not securities.=E2=80=9D (How=
ey, which we discussed on Friday, is the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/32105300.262411/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdXByZW1lLmp1c3RpYS5jb20v=
Y2FzZXMvZmVkZXJhbC91cy8zMjgvMjkzLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa08f6c1f" itemp=
rop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc=
;"> Supreme Court case</a> that created the test for an =E2=80=9Cinvestment=
 contract=E2=80=9D: W.J. Howey Co. sold people some orange groves along wit=
h management services, promising to split the orange profits with the buyer=
s; the Supreme Court found this to be a security.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that this is wrong. You can eat an ora=
nge. XRP is not an orange; it is purely an abstract creation of Ripple, who=
se value comes entirely from the entrepreneurial efforts of Ripple.=C2=A0No=
body bought XRP to eat it. Nor did anyone buy XRP just because they like ow=
ning =E2=80=9Calphanumeric cryptographic sequences.=E2=80=9D There are two =
reasons you might buy XRP:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You want to=C2=A0<em>use=C2=A0</em>XR=
P. XRP is the currency of the XRP blockchain, developed by Ripple=E2=80=99s=
 founders=C2=A0to facilitate cross-border payments and banking services. My=
 understanding is that, in its decade of operation, Ripple has <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32105300.262411/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuY25iYy5jb20vMjAyMy8wNy8xNy9yaXBwbGUtaG9wZXMtanVkZ2UtcnVsaW5nLWluLXNlYy1jY=
XNlLXdpbGwtbGVhZC10by11cy1iYW5rcy11c2luZy14cnAuaHRtbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cBef9d46f8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">not gotten all that far</a> in signing up banks for t=
his payment network, but XRP=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>a functioning cryptocurr=
ency with <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32105300=
.262411/aHR0cHM6Ly9saXZlbmV0LnhycGwub3JnLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6ca94bf=
9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">a blockchain that does transactions</a>, and this is a possibl=
e reason for buying XRP. (It is=C2=A0<em>certainly=C2=A0</em>a possible=C2=
=A0reason for buying=C2=A0<em>other </em>cryptocurrencies, like Ethereum, t=
hat are regularly used to pay for transactions on widely used blockchains.)=
=C2=A0There is essentially no discussion of this possibility in the opinion=
, though, and I do not think that anyone is pounding the table for the view=
 that a lot of the people buying XRP on exchanges were doing so in order to=
 facilitate bank transfers. (If anything, the over-the-counter buyers would=
 include banks who want to actually use XRP =E2=80=94=C2=A0but some OTC buy=
ers explicitly <em>disclaimed </em>the possibility of using XRP.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>)=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You think that the pri=
ce of XRP will go up. Why would it go up? Well, the possibilities include (=
a) =E2=80=9Cgeneral cryptocurrency market trends=E2=80=9D (in Judge Torres=
=E2=80=99 words) and (b) Ripple succeeds in building a widely used payments=
 network, which makes XRP more valuable.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Judge Torres concludes that Ripple=E2=80=99s i=
nstitutional buyers of XRP bought it for Reason 2(b): Ripple told them that=
 it would make XRP more valuable:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Based on the totality of circumsta=
nces, the Court finds that reasonable investors, situated in the position o=
f the Institutional Buyers, would have purchased XRP with the expectation t=
hat they would derive profits from Ripple=E2=80=99s efforts. From Ripple=E2=
=80=99s communications, marketing campaign, and the nature of the Instituti=
onal Sales, reasonable investors would understand that Ripple would use the=
 capital received from its Institutional Sales to improve the market for XR=
P and develop uses for the XRP Ledger, thereby increasing the value of XRP.=
</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Fine. But my contention is that these sales di=
d not consist of (1) XRP=C2=A0<em>plus=C2=A0</em>(2) some set of contracts =
promising that Ripple would use the money to increase the value of XRP. The=
y consisted only of XRP.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" st=
yle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-widt=
h: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important;=
 background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Institutions did not enter into a contract =E2=80=94=C2=A0like th=
e contract in Howey =E2=80=94=C2=A0in which Ripple promised to manage a gro=
ve of XRP for them and give them the proceeds of their success. They just b=
ought XRP. The XRP, and the way in which=C2=A0<em>Ripple advertised it</em>=
, was=C2=A0<em>itself=C2=A0</em>a bet on Ripple=E2=80=99s entrepreneurial e=
fforts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And my second contention is that this is exact=
ly as true in all respects for the retail buyers who bought XRP from Ripple=
 on crypto exchanges. Like the institutional buyers, they were buying a spe=
culative asset that would go up or down, in the long run,=C2=A0<em>exclusiv=
ely due to Ripple=E2=80=99s entrepreneurial efforts</em>. They might not ha=
ve had as sophisticated understanding of these mechanisms as the institutio=
nal investors, but =E2=80=9Cretail investors are under-informed and confuse=
d=E2=80=9D has never in the past been a reason to=C2=A0<em>deny=C2=A0</em>t=
hem the protections of the securities laws.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say that Ripple succeeds wildly =
and XRP becomes the linchpin of a global payments network. Then the XRP tha=
t Ripple=E2=80=99s institutional investors bought would go up, and they wou=
ld have a good return on their investment. The return on investment would c=
ome<em>=C2=A0exclusively=C2=A0</em>from the increasing value of their XRP: =
They had no=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>contracts with Ripple, nothing else th=
at would entitle them to any return outside of their XRP. The XRP, for them=
,=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>the =E2=80=9Csecurity=E2=80=9D; it is the speculati=
ve instrument that they invested money in hoping to get a return from Rippl=
e=E2=80=99s efforts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that is exactly as true, in exactly the sa=
me way, for the retail investors who bought XRP on the exchange. Those reta=
il investors are in complete commonality with the institutional investors; =
they bought the same thing and have exactly the same exposure to exactly th=
e same risks. If Ripple succeeds wildly, a person who bought 100 XRP from R=
ipple on the exchange will get exactly the same benefit as the institution =
who bought 100 XRP from Ripple directly. If XRP is a security in the hands =
of that institution, because it was =E2=80=9Can investment of money in a co=
mmon enterprise with profits to come solely from the efforts of others,=E2=
=80=9D then I think it is a security in the hands of the exchange buyer: sa=
me money, same enterprise, same profits from same efforts of same others.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And my third contention is that they bought th=
em for the same reasons. Sure sure sure: Some retail investors who bought X=
RP on the exchange from Ripple did not actually see Ripple=E2=80=99s advert=
isements, its website, its white paper, its Reddit posts, its YouTube video=
s, or the other public statements in which Ripple said that it would work t=
o=C2=A0increase the value of XRP, the public statements that Judge Torres t=
hought made XRP a security with respect to the institutional investors. But=
 it would be very strange indeed if nobody did, if everybody bought XRP sol=
ely because they liked alphanumeric sequences. Surely Ripple=E2=80=99s wide=
spread=C2=A0<em>advertising of XRP as an investment in its business=C2=A0</=
em>is what caused people generally to want to buy XRP; it=E2=80=99s what cr=
eated the market for XRP.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if you bought XRP without ever seeing a=
ny of those advertisements, just because you logged onto a crypto exchange =
and saw the price of XRP going up and thought =E2=80=9Cokay I=E2=80=99ll bu=
y that,=E2=80=9D I would argue that you were buying a security just like th=
ose institutional investors. Meta Platforms Inc. stock does not become any =
less stock because you don=E2=80=99t buy it directly from Meta, or because =
you have not read Meta=E2=80=99s securities filings. The statements that a =
company makes to a buyer of its securities create the market for those secu=
rities, and if you are buying the securities in the aftermarket it is ultim=
ately because of those statements.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In Ripple,=C2=A0Judge Torres found that Ripple=
 went around making public statements promising to build a business to make=
 XRP more valuable, and she found that those statements were enough to make=
 Ripple=E2=80=99s XRP sales securities offerings,=C2=A0<em>if you could pro=
ve that the buyers read them</em>, as the institutional buyers did.=C2=A0Bu=
t since you can=E2=80=99t prove that about anonymous buyers on the exchange=
, on exchange-sales can never be securities offerings. Ripple could have pu=
t ads on the subway and on television and on Twitter saying =E2=80=9Cbuy XR=
P and we will use your money to build an ecosystem and make you rich,=E2=80=
=9D and then sold XRP on exchanges, and it would not, in the logic of this =
opinion, be a securities offering, because no buyer of XRP on the exchange =
could be=C2=A0<em>sure=C2=A0</em>they were buying it from Ripple, and no co=
urt could be=C2=A0<em>sure=C2=A0</em>that the buyers had seen the ads. I ju=
st don=E2=80=99t think that can be the way securities law works?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The implications of this decision are very str=
ange. Here is one:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A company can create a crypto token, =
declare that there are 100 billion tokens, and issue=C2=A0<em>all=C2=A0</em=
>of them to itself. No mining, no decentralization, just 100% owned by one =
company.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The token can have=C2=A0<=
em>no=C2=A0</em>use: It can=E2=80=99t be used to run smart contracts or pay=
 for services on a network or even to make international payments; it can=
=C2=A0<em>only=C2=A0</em>be traded on exchanges for dollars.</li>=09<li sty=
le=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The company can go around advertising, publicly,=
 in every venue, to every retail and institutional investor, that the token=
 will be incredibly valuable due to the company=E2=80=99s efforts to create=
 an ecosystem and build its network.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px=
;">The company can even=C2=A0<em>explicitly say that it will share the prof=
its of its business=C2=A0</em>with token holders, by using profits to do bu=
ybacks.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Then it can sell the token=
 to public investors on crypto exchanges to raise money to build the busine=
ss.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This is not a security, <em>be=
cause no one can prove that the anonymous buyers on the exchange saw the=C2=
=A0advertisements,=C2=A0</em>and so not subject to securities laws.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am not saying that this is actually what Rip=
ple did, though it is close. (Ripple does not do No. 4, and arguably No. 2 =
isn=E2=80=99t quite true of XRP.) I am saying: Look at that list and tell m=
e that the token is not a speculative investment in a business, tell me tha=
t it is not, in the Supreme Court=E2=80=99s words in Howey, one of =E2=80=
=9Cthe countless and variable schemes devised by those who seek the use of =
the money of others on the promise of profits.=E2=80=9D Tell me that this i=
s not what the securities laws were meant to regulate.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, I should say, a reasonable answer to all =
of this might be =E2=80=9Csure, there should be a disclosure and regulatory=
 regime for crypto offerings that is roughly parallel to the one for securi=
ties, but that addresses the unique features of crypto.=E2=80=9D And I <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32105300.262411/aHR0cH=
